review_blob: Murky red hue with a minimal tan head, needs a bit of encouragement to pull out the carbonation in the glass. Aroma is bizarre- it reminds me of a cinnamon cereal, maybe from the chestnut? There is a bit of sweetness in there too, wood, cinnamon, grain. One can smell the tartness. This beer packs a wallop- slightly fruity and sweet, big mouth-puckering tartness, a little backyard funk and again a hint of cinnamon. Finish is bone-dry, lingering sweetness like after eating fresh raspberries. Funky, tart, a little sweet, a little herbal- I dig this beer.

Pours a hazy orange with minimal head. Aroma of citrus fruit and earthy hops. Sugary and sweet, again citrusy hops (orange and lemon)... Medium bodied and syrupy as all hell. Tons of residual sugar coats the mouth, totally knocks down the hop profile... If the hop character was knotched up and the sweetness was knotched down this could be a stellar fruit-forward APA. As it is, drinkable but not overwhelming or totally off-putting.

Pours a bright hazy pale-orange. Nose is a little weak, but the right notes are there - coriander, orange, a little grass. Packs a bright orange-zest punch, quite sweet but not off-putting. Mellow coriander and grass taste as well, Belgian yeast is not on showcase by any means. Medium-bodied, a little too syrupy, carbonation is solid and finish is dry. Its 1,000,000 degrees outside so this beer is definitely killing it in the moment. That said, this beer is all oranges, if you want a little more yeast-funk try again.

Pours a deep red-orange, almost brown, with a thin tan head out the can. Aroma is big on floral hops -- dank and weedy -- slight sweetness and caramel.

Big caramelized sugar punch, woody/floral hop build really dries things up. Almost a char-like character on the finish, like cedar or something.

Super earthy IPA, sounds east coast enough for me. Solid showing, but not my style.

Pours a deep amber, tan head. Piney hop aroma, caramelized sugar. Very mellow, definitely doesnt jump out of the glass.Taste is  big piney hops, fairly bitter but not overblown. Carries some carmel character  but not overloaded with residual sugar. Medium bodied with a very dry finish. Seems like a crossover between a EPA and APA, getting up there at 6%abv. Solid showing for my first DC beer.

011813 bottle date

Pours a nice rich dark brown with a frothy milk chocolate head.

Aroma is mostly chocolate with a toasty char, a bit of residual sweetness.

Damn this is a smooth silky porter.. Big chocolate with a bit of roast, medium bodied with low carbonation. Finishes suuuper mellow and creamy, slightly dry and a hint of lingering roast but it doesnt bomb out your palate.

Always happy to pick up some Maine Beer when Im on the coast, I would be reaching for this as my go-to porter if it landed in MN.

330ml bottle from bluondous 070613 expiration

Deep red orange with a slight head. Smells of light citrus hops and a bit of grass. Citrus in the hop profile, grapefruit rind and a light malt backbone adds a nice sweetness. It has a nice brightness with a fairly dry bitter finish. Although Iceland has a lot of European overtones their beer seems to err on the side of the USA. 5.9% is on the lower end for an IPA, but it definitely doesnt drink like a straight up pale. Through the course of a bottle it finishes a bit murky and there is a hint of astringency, but nothing like some of the terrible malty bombs of an IPA one sees stateside.
beer_name: Borg lfur India Pale Ale Nr. 3

review_blob:
Bottle -> Mason Jar (Kentucky...right?)

Pours a deep amber-red with a thick tan head. Aroma is sweet toasted malt and heavy on the rye, like a loaf of bread. Big rye presence, with a bit of light citrus on the tip of the tongue. The hop additions cut through any anticipated malty sweetness, leaving only the citrus and rye. Medium body and carbonation, a bit creamy. Since internet is my only reference point as to what a Kentucky Common is, I am disappointed to not catch any sourness in this beer. Overall, a solid rye-amber ale with enough hops to keep things in check.

Pours a hazy opaque yellow. Estery nose, a bit of musty citrus. Taste of slightly tart green apple, lemon, banana sweetness. Medium body, nice effervescence which fades a bit over the course if the 750.

Picked up a bottle of this and Moe when I was in Boston last week... So far, quite impressed with them.. I digress. Zoe pours a deep deeeeep red with a creamy tan head. Aroma of citrus and roast, a bit caramel-y. Taste matches up well, a bit of creamy fruityness, roasted malt, sweet caramel. A bit of hop bite and a lack of astringency, which seems so prevalent in ambers, set this beer off. Ambers definitely arent my go to style, but this beer holds up nicely, a clean crisp finish goes a long way in my book.

Aha! The TSA only smashed one of my bottles... Had this on tap at Lord Hobo in Boston and decided to bring some home.

Pours a nice hazy yellow with a bright thick head. Sweet citrusy aroma, fresh grass clippings, and a bit of tropical fruit.

Light bodied, crisp carbonation. Wonderful grassy, citrusy taste, hoppy bitter finish. So fresh, so clean. A bit of yeastyness.

A truly amazing lager.. Dances around on the tongue like a fresh west coast apa.. I remember a bit more fruity character on draft but it holds up really well in the bottle. (bottled aug 28, 2012)

Pours a deep dark red-orange thin head which quickly recedes. Aroma of herbs and spices, a little pumpkin pulp but not much... Almost a bit savory on the nose. Light bodied, thin taste with a fair bit of carbonation. Pretty disappointing, hints of nutmeg and cinnamon, quite dry. Not very much pumpkin for a pumpkin beer.. Ill stick with some of the other fall specialties.

750ml Bottled Aug 14

Pours a golden dark yellow, thick off-white head. Sweet dank aroma, a bit of spiciness or pepperyness. Quite crisp and bitter, a reaaaaal weedy beer, you can tell these dudes listen to Phish. Citrusy and slightly sweet, the hops really shine through. Exciting new beer here in MN, varies every time I try it as they have tap and rotating cask versions in the taproom, as well as bottles. It will be interesting to see what its like in a can in the next month or so.
Clear piercing yellow with almost no head. Super grassy with a bit of sweetness on the nose. Grassy hoppy bite which fades quickly, not overly sweet. Well done for a crisp summertime lager.

Cans arent too fresh out here in New York City, 4/13/12 on the bottom.

Dank nose, real dank, like someone just weeded the garden if you know what Im saying. Great floral hop bite, with a smooth bitter linger. Lacking a bit in the carbonation, but retains that sticky frothy head I always associate with Oskar beers.

One day theyll distribute in MN... One day. Until then Ill be on the lookout for a fresh can somewhere outside of NYC.
beer_name: Oskar Blues Deviant Dales India Pale Ale

review_blob: A bright clear yellow, with a pungent citrusy nose. A touch of sweet marmalade, and a bit of booze. Follows with a sweet rich orange flavor with a sharp hop presence. A fair body for an APA, not surprising at 6.2%. Floral hop finish, with a lingering twinge from the carbonation.

Citrusy aroma clementine and tangerine, with a bit of piney resinousness, very subtle alcohol. Bubbly bright orange with a nice white head. Light bodied, big hop bite for an APA. Smooth body with nice light carbonation. A great hopped up pale, not super complex, but well done none the less.

2011 edition 12oz Bottle into a snifter.

Aroma is quite boozy and sweet. A big brown sugar and molasses character.  Pours a deep red with a fair amount of clarity, tan head with nice retention, keeps up a cappuccino-esq appearance. Lots of dark fruit tastes, hoppy bite, not to hot on the alcohol but has some burn in the finish. Creamy mouthfeel with a fair bit of carbonation. 

Super cheap at $7.99 a 4-pack. Complex flavor, too sweet and boozy on the nose for me. Ill be looking forward to enjoying one of these in a couple years.

12oz Bottle into a snifter. Pours a deep brown with a tan head, body looks a bit thin. Aroma heavy on vanilla, sweet alcohol and a bit of woodiness. Nice vanilla and chocolate flavor, big in alcohol as well but lacking the burn. Drinks super well, even fresh. Mouthfeel is a bit thin for an imperial with a fair amount of carbonation. Smooth finish with a lingering woody flavor. With a bit more body I think this beer would have a lot of hype on it, for now Ill take the readily available 4-packs here in MN.
beer_name: Central Waters Brewers Reserve Bourbon Barrel Stout

review_blob: Light bodied and fairly easy drinking, a fair amount of carbonation with a crisp finish. Aroma and taste of brown sugar. The spruce is lacking, but overall a nice session-able wintertime ale.
